Normant In connection with the synthesis of polyketide-derived polycyclic  natural  products  such  as  11  and  22  (Scheme  1), we  required  a  viable  means  for  the  construction  of  β-hy- droxynaphthoate  scaffold  (red).3  For  this  purpose,  we  be- came  intrigued  by  the  biosynthesis  of  this  class  of  natural products,4 in which this partial structure emerges at a later stage via the intramolecular aldol condensation as exempli- fied in Scheme 1 (A). By the successive intramolecular aldol condensations,  polyketide  chain  A  is  converted  into  an- throne B bearing an acetyl and an acetoacetate side chains, undergoing further condensation to provide the tetracyclic compound C.

Hinted by this process, we came up with an idea of con- structing  β-hydroxynaphthoate  IV  via  a  two-step  cascade process  from  β,δ-diketo  ester  I  and  arylsilane  II  having  an ortho-leaving group (Scheme 2). More specifically, we envi- sioned that β-keto ester III, a condensation precursor of IV, would  be  assembled  via  acyl-alkylation  of  enolate  I′  and benzyne II′5 generated from I and II under basic conditions, allowing a successive intramolecular aldol condensation to give IV.6,7 Given the case, two questions would arise: (1) Is β,δ-diketo  ester  derivative  I  applicable  to  the  acyl-alkyl- ation reaction of benzyne? (2) What is a suitable base to fa- cilitate the whole process? Received: 02.06.2016 Accepted after revision: 16.06.2016 Published online: 19.07.2016 DOI: 10.1055/s-0035-1562514; Art ID: ss-2016-c0400-op Abstract  A  variety  of  highly  functionalized  β-hydroxynaphthoate  de- rivatives are prepared by a two-step protocol: (1) acyl-alkylation of ben- zynes  with  ketodioxinones  and  (2)  intramolecular  aldol  condensation. The substitution pattern of the products is related to polycyclic natural products derived from the type-II polyketide biosynthesis. Key words  ketodioxinones, benzynes, acyl-alkylation, aldol condensa- tion, cascade reaction © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synthesis 2016, 48, A–H Scheme 1   β-Hydroxynaphthoate in aromatic polyketides Scheme 2   Two-step construction of β-hydroxynaphthoate 12 examples up to 86% yield

. l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C In this paper, we wish to report an affirmative answer to this  scenario,  opening  a  way  for  the  facile  construction  of highly functionalized β-hydroxynaphthoate scaffolds. For  a  pilot  experiment,  o-trimethylsilylphenyl  triflate (3a)8  and  β,δ-diketo  ester  4  were  employed  (Scheme  3). Upon treatment of 3a and 4 with KF and 18-crown-6 in THF (r.t., 5.5 h), the starting materials were smoothly consumed, affording  a  mixture  of  many  products.  Two  products  were isolated, one of which was the desired β-hydroxynaphtho- ate 5 (6% yield) and the other was the isomeric naphthoate 6 (13% yield). The formation of 5, albeit in low yield, indicated the via- bility of the projected reaction. However, several issues on the use of 4 were revealed (Scheme 4, A): (1) Considerable decomposition  of  4  proved  problematic  under  the  basic conditions,9 and (2) the intermediary aryl anion V, generat- ed  by  the  nucleophilic  addition  of  4  to  benzyne,  has  two electrophilic sites, namely C5 and C3, where a nonselective attack occurred, leading to the formation of both 5 and 6. Scheme 3   Pilot experiment Scheme 4   Problem and solution © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synthesis 2016, 48, A–H

The latter notion led us to focus on ketodioxinone VI as a β,δ-diketo ester surrogate (Scheme 4, B).10 We envisioned that,  after  the  formation  of  aryl  anion  VII,  the  subsequent addition would occur at the ketone carbonyl group in a re- gioselective  manner  to  provide  naphthoate  IX  via  ketone VIII. Along  these  lines,  we  focused  on  the  screening  of  the base, using the reaction of o-silylaryl triflate 3a (1.5 equiv) with  ketodioxinone  7a11  as  a  benchmark  (Table  1).  Upon treatment of 3a and 7a with KF (3 equiv) in the presence of 18-crown-6  (3  equiv)  in  THF  (r.t.,  7  h),  the  corresponding naphthoate 8a was not obtained (Table 1, entry 1). Howev- er, ketone 9 was obtained in 65% yield, an intermediate en route to 8a, where a small amount of ketone 10 was co-pro- duced (ca. 11% yield). This result suggested that the initial acyl-alkylation proceeded as expected, while the latter al- dol  condensation  was  relatively  slow  under  these  condi- tions. Formation of ketone 10 could be ascribed to protona- tion of the intermediary aryl anion species (see VII, Scheme 4).  During  the  prolonged  reaction  time  (5  days)  under  the same  conditions,  intramolecular  aldol  condensation  pro- ceeded slowly, but steadily to give 8a in 67% yield (entry 2). By  employing  CsF  or  TBAF  as  a  base,  8a  was  obtained  in lower yield (entries 3 and 4). Table 1   Optimization of Base for the Formation of Naphthoate 8aa

a Unless otherwise indicated, all reactions were performed with 3a (1.5  equiv), 7a (1.0 equiv), base (3 equiv), and 18-crown-6 (3 equiv) in THF  (0.02 M) at r.t. b Isolated yield. c Without 18-crown-6. d At 50 °C. e Unreacted 7a (66%). . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C At this juncture, our attention was turned to the use of alkali  metal  carbonates  (Table  1,  entries  5–8).12  It  turned out that the choice of a suitable counter cation was decisive for  realizing  high  yields:  By  using  K2CO3  or  Rb2CO3,  longer reaction time was required for full conversion, and the cor- responding  naphthoate  8a  was  obtained  only  in  moderate yield (entries 5 and 6). On the other hand, Cs2CO3 was found to  allow  for  facile  conversion  (13  h)  to  provide  8a  in  80% yield (entry 7). Furthermore, by raising the temperature (50 °C), the reaction time was shortened (4.5 h), affording 8a in 86% yield (entry 8). Note that the use of 18-crown-6 was es- Table 2   Syntheses of Various Naphthoates via Benzyne Acyl-Alkylation and Aldol Condensation Cascadea

a Unless otherwise indicated, all reactions were performed with 3 (1.5 equiv), 7 (1.0 equiv), Cs2CO3 (3 equiv), and 18-crown-6 (3 equiv) in THF (0.02 M) at r.t. b Isolated yield. c In THF and Et2O (1:1) at 50 °C. d Conditions: 3c (2 equiv), Cs2CO3 (4 equiv), and 18-crown-6 (4 equiv) in THF and Et2O (v/v = 1:1) at 50 °C. e Unreacted 7a (ca. 11%). f Conditions: 3d (2 equiv), Cs2CO3 (4 equiv), and 18-crown-6 (4 equiv) at 50 °C. © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synthesis 2016, 48, A–H sential as evidenced by the reaction in its absence that gave none of 8a, where unreacted 7a was recovered (entry 9). Having  found  the  optimized  conditions,  the  scope  of this  reaction  was  examined,  which  led  us  to  confirm  its broad  applicability  (Table  2).  Entries  1–4  show  the  reac- tions  of  benzyne  precursor  3a  with  other  ketodioxinones 7b–e10d,e  having  various  substituents  at  the  C5  position. Aryl-substituted  ketodioxinone  7b  reacted  with  3a  to  give the corresponding naphthoate 8b in good yield (Table 2, en- try 1). Although the furyl group in 7c was potentially prone to  a  side  reaction  with  benzyne,  that  is,  Diels–Alder  reac- tion,13 clean reaction occurred to give 8c in 73 % yield (entry . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C

2).  When  7d  having  a  benzyloxymethyl  group  was  used, naphthoate 8d was obtained in 59% yield (entry 3). The re- action of 7e was an example of a branched substrate, which, albeit with an increased steric demand around the nucleop- hilic  site,  underwent  smooth  reaction  to  give  8e  bearing two  methyl  groups  at  the  C5-  and  C10-positions  in  58% yield  (entry  4).  Various  benzyne  precursors  having  an alkoxy group(s) proved applicable (entries 5–10). It turned out that 3-benzyloxy derivative 3b was much more reactive than 3a, leading to faster reactions with ketodioxinones 7a– c and 7e (3–9 h) to afford 8f–i in satisfactory yields (entries 5–8).  While  the  reaction  of  3,5-dimethoxy  derivative  3c with 7a proceeded slowly (15 h) to give 8j in moderate yield (entry  9),  4,5-dimethoxy  derivative  3d  smoothly  under- went  the  reaction  with  7a  (5.5  h)  to  afford  8k  in  higher yield  than  that  of  3c  (entry  10).  It  should  be  noted  that since both 3c and 3d decomposed more rapidly than 3a and 3b under the standard conditions (Cs2CO3, 18-crown-6, r.t.), the improved protocol with an increased amount (2 equiv) of 3c or 3d was applied for smooth consumption of 7a.

Importantly, naphthoates 8f–j were obtained as a single regioisomer, attributed to the regioselective attack of eno- late XI at the β-position to the alkoxy group of benzyne X (Scheme 5). The enhanced electrophilicity of the β-carbon of  X  is  derived  from  the  inductive  effect  of  an  alkoxy group14 and/or the geometrical distortion.15 The potential of naphthoate 8a was demonstrated by re- alizing  the  concise  entry  to  β-hydroxynaphthoate  5 (Scheme  6):  Upon  treatment  of  8a  with  Cs2CO3  in  MeOH and THF (r.t.), smooth solvolysis proceeded to give ester 5 in 85%  yield.  On  the  other  hand,  it  turned  out  that  ketone  9 was also converted into ester 5 upon treatment with K2CO3 in MeOH (r.t.), where methanolysis followed by intramolec- ular aldol condensation (or vice versa) proceeded smoothly. Furthermore, thermal conditions also proved applicable for this transformation: Heating of 9 in a mixed solvent of tolu- ene and MeOH (110 °C) in a sealed tube gave the intermedi- ary  β-keto  ester  XII  via  thermal  generation  of  the  acylke- tene  species  followed  by  addition  of  MeOH,16  undergoing spontaneous condensation to afford ester 5 in 86% yield.17 Scheme 5   Rationale for the regioselectivity © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synthesis 2016, 48, A–H

Scheme 7 shows the application of this approach to the construction of isoindolinone 13, a key structural motif in the lactonamycin-type natural products. Starting from o-si- lylaryl  triflate  3b  and  ketodioxinone  7f  with  an  amino- methyl group at the C5 position,10e we had planned a cas- cade reaction by employing the combination of Cs2CO3 and 18-crown-6.  However,  we  were  disappointed  by  the  com- plete  failure  of  the  attempted  reaction,  and  the  desired naphthoate 8l was not obtained. Pleasingly,  however,  the  projected  transformation  was realized by a stepwise protocol: Upon treatment of 3b and 7f with KF and 18-crown-6 (THF, r.t.), acyl-alkylation reac- tion cleanly proceeded to give ketone 11 in 53% yield, which could  be  converted  into  β-hydroxynaphthoate  12  by  heat- Scheme 6   Conversion into β-hydroxynaphthoate 5 Scheme 7   Construction of the isoindolinone core of 2 K2CO3              MeOH              r.t., 93% . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C ing in methanol (vide supra) in 87% yield. Finally, acid de- tachment of the N-Boc group triggered lactamization to af- ford the target isoindolinone 13 in 85% yield. In summary, we have developed a novel cascade process to  construct  the  β-hydroxynaphthoate  scaffolds  via  ben- zyne acyl-alkylation with ketodioxinones followed by intra- molecular aldol condensation. Further work on the applica- tion to natural product synthesis is underway in our labora- tory.

All  reactions  utilizing  air-  or  moisture-sensitive  reagents  were  per- formed  in  dried  glassware  under  an  atmosphere  of  dry  argon.  THF, Et2O, and CH2Cl2 (anhyd; Kanto Chemical Co., Inc.) were purified un- der argon using a solvent purification unit (Wako Pure Chemical In- dustries, Ltd.). Toluene (anhyd; Kanto Chemical Co., Inc.) and MeOH (anhyd; Nacalai Tesque, Inc.) was used as received. 1,1,1,3,3,3-Hexa- methyldisilazane was distilled prior to use according to standard pro- tocols. KF, CsF, and Cs2CO3 were dried (100 °C, 1 mmHg, 2 h) prior to use.  Other  reagents  were  used  without  further  purification.  For  TLC analysis,  Merck  precoated  plates  (silica  gel  60  F254,  0.25  mm)  were used.  Silica  gel  preparative  TLC  (PTLC)  was  performed  using  plates prepared from Merck Silica gel 60 PF254 (Art7747). For flash column chromatography, silica gel 60N (Spherical, neutral, 63–210 μm) from Kanto  Chemical  was  used. 2,2,5-Trimethyl-4H-naphtho[2,3-d][1,3]dioxin-4-one (8a); Typical  Procedure A  flame-dried  two-necked  flask  charged  with  18-crown-6  (169  mg, 0.641 mmol) was evacuated (1 mmHg) at r.t. for 1 h, to which were added o-silylaryl triflate 3a (94.6 mg, 0.317 mmol), ketodioxinone 7a (38.4 mg, 0.208 mmol), and THF (10.5 mL). To the mixture was added Cs2CO3 (205 mg, 0.628 mmol) and stirred for 4.5 h at 50 °C. The reac- tion was quenched by adding sat. aq NH4Cl and the mixture was ex- tracted with EtOAc (3 ×). The combined organic layers were washed with  brine,  dried  (Na2SO4),  and  concentrated  in  vacuo.  The  residue was  purified  by  PTLC  (hexane/EtOAc  =  2:1)  to  afford  naphthoate  8a (43.3 mg, 86%) and ketodioxinone 10 (3.6 mg, 7%) both as a white sol- id.  Recrystallization  of  8a  from  hexane/CH2Cl2  gave  8a  as  colorless prisms; mp: 138.6–139.5 °C; Rf = 0.50 (hexane/EtOAc = 5:1).
